Py4Hw User Guide> 10.3 Schematic Visualization Internals¶

Next: 10.4 Comparing with other Python based HDLs¶

The visualization of circuit schematics is implemented from scratch in the framework. It is based on the idea that we have multiple columns. Every circuit is assigned to a column first.

I use a grid where I can place symbols. Only one symbol can be placed in a grid cell. I place the inputs of the circuit in the first column, the instances in the second column and the outputs in the third column.

Then, I analyze the dependencies between symbols. If a symbol input is connected to another symbol output it is placed in the column of the source symbol + 1. To handle loops we do a DFS-based Longest Path layering. outputs are moved to the last column.

Then I create passthrough symbols to avoid having connections between non consecutive columns.

For feedback loops I use a feedback start and feedback stop special symbols and passthrough symbols. Although they represent reverse connections (from right to left) they are connected in forward order to simplify the processing. So feedback stop connects both to the sink symbol and the passthrough chain until it reaches the feedback start. The source symbol of a feedback also connects to this feedback start symbol.

def print_matrix():
    
    mat = sch.symbol_matrix 
        
    nr, nc = mat.shape
    data = np.empty((nr,nc), dtype=object)

    for r in range(nr):
        for c in range(nc):
            sym = mat[r,c]
            if not(sym is None):
                data[r,c] = sym.name 
            else:
                data[r,c] = ''
    
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=data)
    display(df)
        
    return
In [3]:
def print_adjacency_matrix(r_syms, c_syms, am):
    nr = len(r_syms)
    nc = len(c_syms)
    
    r_names = [item.name for item in r_syms]
    c_names = [item.name for item in c_syms]
    
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=am, columns=c_names, index=r_names)
    
    display(df)

The schematic object allows to control various things of the visualization process.

The schematic visualization process uses a grid to place symbols like input and output ports and instances. Each grid position can only contain one object.

By analyzing the relations between symbols, we can create an adjacency matrix.

In [4]:
sys = py4hw.HWSystem()
reset = sys.wire('reset')
inc = sys.wire('inc')
q = sys.wire('q', 8)
co = sys.wire('co')

counter = py4hw.ModuloCounter(sys, 'mod7', 7, reset, inc, q, co)
sch = py4hw.Schematic(counter, placeAndRoute=False)

Step 1 Place Inputs¶

This is the first step, it assigns inputs to the first column of the schematic. For convenience, we assign a name to the block. We actually place the inputs in the grid, no x,y setting. We need to call replaceAsColRow to do it.

Symbols do not know their position at creation, but after calling replaceAsColRow they are assigned pixel coordinates (x,y) and matrix coordinates matching the information from symbol_matrix.

Step 4 Column Assignment¶

This stage assigns a column (layer) to each symbol based on data-dependency depth in the circuit graph and then maps symbols to matrix coordinates.

The circuit is modeled as a directed graph where edges represent signal dependencies. Inputs are fixed in column 0. Each logic instance is assigned to a column equal to one plus the maximum column of its source dependencies (i.e., DFS-based longest-path layering). Feedback loops are explicitly handled via cycle detection to prevent infinite recursion during depth computation.

Outputs are placed in a final column after all logic instances.

Once column indices are determined, symbols are ordered within each column and placed into symbol_matrix[row, col], where the row corresponds to the symbols position within its column and the column corresponds to its computed dependency level.

Step 5 Move Right¶

Some sources are placed far from the sinks because the sinks have other sources in righter columns. We can reduce this distance by placing this far sources to the immediate column before the sink.

Step 7 Net creation¶

Nets are objects that connect elements.

Nets are point to point connections. They collect a source symbol with a sink symbol. Symbols can have multiple ports, so nets also collect the ports of the connection endpoints. Nets are later routed to be rendered into polygons

Since elements that have a connection to the left of the diagonal are feedback loops, we indentify the sink symbols of this elements (the ones in the columns) and create an empty column in the symbol matrix before them

Step 8 Passthrough creation¶

We create elements so that connections are never connecting elements from non-contiguous levels. An exception are feedback loops.

The idea is that we can have

         level 1      level 2    level 3
          +---+                  +---+
       +->| A | ---+------------>| B |
       |  +---+    |             +---+
       |           |  +---+
       |           +->| C |--+
       |              +---+  |
       +---------------------+

and we convert it to

level 1   level 2      level 3      level 4
 +---+     +---+       +-----+      +---+
 |Fe |--+->| A | ---+--| pt1 |----->| B |
 +---+  |  +---+    |  +-----+      +---+
        |           |  +---+        +----+
        |           +->| C |------->| Fs |
        |              +---+        |    |
        |   +-----+    +-----+      |    |
        +---| pt1 |----| pt1 |----->|    |
            +-----+    +---+        +----+

then, some connections no longer have information about the connecting endpoint. Is that a problem ?

To make it simple passthrough channels should insert a row in the symbol matrix just below the block point.

Feedback channels should insert a row at the bottom of the symbol matrix.

Identify Mergeable Passthrough Symbols¶

If a symbol is connected to two (or more) passthrough symbols in the same level that are in close row, we can merge the passthrough symbol.

Two mergeable passthrough symbols have the following setup

 A ---> pt1 ---> B
   ---> pt2 ---> C

than can be converted into

 A ---> pt1 ---> B
            ---> C

In this case we remove pt2. To do it, we detect that A has two sinks that are passthrough, we remove the net from A to pt2, remove pt2, and change the source of the last net to pt1.

or this one

A --> pt1 --> C
B --> pt2 -->

that can be converted into

A --> pt1 --> C
B -->

In this case we remove pt2. To do it, we detect that C has two sources that are passthrough, we remove the net from pt2 to C, remove pt2, and change the sink of the net from B to pt1.

We have an additional case with feedback start symbols

A --> fA1 
A --> fA2 
pt1 --> fA1
pt2 --> fA2

that could be converted into

A --> fA1 
pt1 --> fA1
pt2 --> fA1

In this case we remove fA2. To do it, we detect that A has two sinks that are feedback starts. If both feedback starts are in consecutive rows we remove the second one, remove the nets pointing to it, and change the sink of the nets pointing to it for the first node.

Move inputs and outputs¶

In [17]:
def moveCloseRow(self, sym, dstr):
    nr, nc = self.symbol_matrix.shape
    
    if (sym.r == dstr):
        return
    
    freer = [r for r in range(nr) if self.symbol_matrix[r, sym.c] is None] # free rows
    freer.sort(key=lambda r: abs(dstr - r))
    
    if len(freer) == 0:
        return
    
    # Move it to the free row
    self.symbol_matrix[sym.r, sym.c] = None
    self.symbol_matrix[freer[0], sym.c] = sym
    sym.r = freer[0]
    
def moveUpToRow(self, sym, dstr):
    nr, nc = self.symbol_matrix.shape
    
    if (sym.r == dstr):
        return
    
    freer = [r for r in range(sym.r+1, dstr+1) if self.symbol_matrix[r, sym.c] is None] # free rows
    freer.sort(key=lambda r: abs(dstr - r))
    
    if len(freer) == 0:
        return
    
    # Move it to the free row
    self.symbol_matrix[sym.r, sym.c] = None
    self.symbol_matrix[freer[0], sym.c] = sym
    sym.r = freer[0]

nr, nc = sch.symbol_matrix.shape

tomove = []

# move inputs
for r in range(nr):
    sym = sch.symbol_matrix[r, 0]
    
    if (sym is None):
        continue
    
    avgr = int(np.mean([sym.r for sym in sch.getSinkSymbols(sym)]))
    
    tomove.append((sym, avgr))
# move outputs
for r in range(nr):
    sym = sch.symbol_matrix[r, nc-1]
    
    if (sym is None):
        continue
    
    avgr = int(np.mean([sym.r for sym in sch.getSourceSymbols(sym)]))
    
    tomove.append((sym, avgr))
    
for sym, avgr in tomove:    
    print('moving', sym.name, 'to', avgr)
    
    moveCloseRow(sch, sym, avgr)
    
sch.replaceAsColRow()
sch.routeNets(mode='direct')
sch.createRender()
sch.drawAll(debug=True)

self = sch

active_chains = [[net] for net in self.getNets() if not(isinstance(net.source , py4hw.PassthroughSymbol)) and isinstance(net.sink , py4hw.PassthroughSymbol)]
final_chains = []

while active_chains:
    next_generation = []
    
    for chain in active_chains:
        last_sym = chain[-1].sink
        
        # Find all outgoing nets from the current tip of the chain
        outgoing_nets = [net for net in self.getNets() if net.source == last_sym]
        
        # Filter for nets that continue into more Virtual/Passthrough symbols
        continuations = [n for n in outgoing_nets if isinstance(n.sink, py4hw.PassthroughSymbol)]
        
        if not continuations:
            # Chain has ended (hits a real gate or an output)
            final_chains.append(chain)
        else:
            # Handle diversions: Create a new chain branch for every destination
            for net in continuations:
                # Duplicate the existing path and add the new sink
                new_path = list(chain) 
                new_path.append(net)
                next_generation.append(new_path)
                
    active_chains = next_generation

final_chains.sort(key=len, reverse=True)   

for chain in final_chains:
    print('Net len:', len(chain), end=' = ')
    for net in chain:
        print(net.source.name, '-->', net.sink.name, end=' ')
    print()
    
for i in range(len(final_chains)):

        chain2 = final_chains[j]
        for net in chain:
            if (net in chain2): chain2.remove(net)
        final_chains[j] = chain2

In [25]:
if (False):
    # Sort chains by their starting point Y to keep layout intuitive
    final_chains.sort(key=len, reverse=True)   

    for chain in final_chains:
        nr, nc = self.symbol_matrix.shape

        # 1. Identify all symbols in this chain
        # We include the source and sink of every net in the chain
        chain_symbols = set()
        for net in chain:
            chain_symbols.add(net.source)
            chain_symbols.add(net.sink)

        # 2. Find the vertical "insertion point"
        # We find the max Y of any symbol involved to ensure we 
        # place the chain below its predecessors.
        insertion_row = max(sym.r for sym in chain_symbols) 


        # 4. Shift everything below the insertion point down by 1
        # It is important to iterate through all symbols in the schematic
        for sym in chain_symbols:
            if (sym.r == insertion_row):
                continue
            if (sym.r > insertion_row):
                raise Exception('Not possible')

            # sym.r is < insertion_row move down all elements
            dist = insertion_row - sym.r
            self._expand_symbol_matrix(nr + dist, nc)

            for i in range(nr+dist, sym.r, -1):
                mvsym = self.symbol_matrix[i-dist, sym.c]
                if (mvsym is None):
                    continue
                mvsym.r = i
                self.symbol_matrix[i, sym.c] = mvsym 
                self.symbol_matrix[i-dist, sym.c] = None

    sch.replaceAsColRow()
    sch.routeNets(mode='direct')
    sch.createRender()
    sch.drawAll(debug=True)

def shrinkVirtualSymbols(self):
    nr, nc = self.symbol_matrix.shape
    
    for r in range(nr):
        for c in range(nc):
            sym = self.symbol_matrix[r,c]
            if (sym is None):
                continue
                
            if isinstance(sym, py4hw.VirtualSymbol):
                sym.w, sym.h = 1,1

Detect vertical gaps¶

I think we should find the vertical center of gravity of the graph. Then find vertical gaps and try to compress the graph in the direction of the vertical center of gravity. We should consider chains as a whole object.

For instance, q (and its chain) can be lowered. All the elements have many free cells below.

In [30]:
if (False):
    #print_matrix()

    sch.replaceAsColRow()

    from collections import defaultdict
    source = defaultdict(list)

    for net in sch.getNets():
        c = net.source.c

        source[c].append(net)


    # We move the left elements to match the right ones
    for c in range(nc-1):        
        for net in source[c]:
            #print(f'[{net.source.r}]', net.source.name, '-->' , f'[{net.sink.r}]', net.sink.name)
            #print(sch.symbol_matrix[net.source.r, net.source.c])

            # check if left object can move towards right
            left_dst = net.sink.r - net.source.r
            left_inc = np.sign(left_dst)

            #print('move', left_dst, left_inc)
            lr = net.source.r

            doRun = True
            while (doRun and lr != net.sink.r):
                lr += left_inc
                #print('lr', lr, net.source.c, sch.symbol_matrix[lr, net.source.c])
                doRun = sch.symbol_matrix[lr, net.source.c] == None

                if (doRun):
                    sch.symbol_matrix[lr-left_inc, net.source.c] = None
                    sch.symbol_matrix[lr, net.source.c] = net.source
                    #print('moving to', lr)

    # We move the right elements to match the left ones

    for c in range(nc-2, -1, -1):    
        for net in source[c]:

            # check if right object can move towards the left one
            right_dst = net.source.r - net.sink.r 
            right_inc = np.sign(right_dst)


            rr = net.sink.r

            doRun = True
            while (doRun and rr != net.source.r):
                rr += right_inc

                doRun = sch.symbol_matrix[rr, net.sink.c] == None

                if (doRun):
                    sch.symbol_matrix[rr-right_inc, net.sink.c] = None
                    sch.symbol_matrix[rr, net.sink.c] = net.sink
In [31]:
def compactVertically(self):
    """Remove empty rows within each column after alignment."""
    nr, nc = self.symbol_matrix.shape
    
    for c in range(nc):
        # Collect all symbols in this column in row order
        symbols_in_col = []
        for r in range(nr):
            if self.symbol_matrix[r, c] is not None:
                symbols_in_col.append((r, self.symbol_matrix[r, c]))
        
        # Clear the column
        for r in range(nr):
            self.symbol_matrix[r, c] = None
        
        # Repack from the top, removing gaps
        for new_r, (old_r, symbol) in enumerate(symbols_in_col):
            self.symbol_matrix[new_r, c] = symbol
            symbol.r = new_r
